# Resume Template: Migrate from .md to .docx Template-Based Generation

## Background

Currently:
1. User uploads a [.md](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/README.md) file as template → stored as plain text in the database
2. The LLM in [writer_service.py](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py) receives the markdown text as a "template definition" and generates an entire markdown resume from scratch
3. The **frontend** ([ResumeManagement.tsx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/frontend/components/ResumeManagement.tsx)) then converts that markdown output into a [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) using the JS [docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) library, creating a brand-new file

**Problems with this approach:**
- Markdown symbols leak into the .docx (bullets `*`, `#`, `**bold**`, etc.)
- Formatting is generic — headings, fonts, spacing are not as designed by the user

**New approach:**
1. User uploads a [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) file as the template
2. The template file contains placeholder tokens like `{skills}`, `{projects}`, `{Content of Cover letter: 4 paragraphs}`
3. The backend reads the [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx), extracts all `{key}` and `{key: "explain"}` tokens, tells the LLM to only generate content for those keys, and then replaces those tokens in the [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) in-place
4. The resulting [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) (a copy of the template with replaced content) is returned to the user — preserving all fonts, tables, spacing, and layouts

---

## Potential Conflicts & Design Decisions

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Conflict 1: Template stored as text vs binary**
> Currently `template_content` in the DB is type `TEXT` (stores markdown as a utf-8 string). A [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) is a binary file. We have two options:
> - **Option A (Recommended):** Store the template as a **Base64-encoded string** in the existing `template_content` column (no DB migration needed).
> - **Option B:** Store the template file on disk (e.g., inside the Docker volume) and keep only the path in the DB.
>
> ✅ **We will use Option A (Base64)** — no schema migration, simpler deployment, consistent with existing pattern.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Conflict 2: The LLM currently returns a full markdown document**
> The content generation logic in [writer_service.py](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py) will need to change: instead of generating a full document, it will now receive only the extracted placeholder keys and return a **JSON dict** of `{key: generated_content}` pairs. The LLM quality/logic for each individual section stays the same; we're only changing what it outputs.
>
> ✅ **We will modify [writer_service.py](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py) to generate per-key content** while keeping all experience/job context injection logic intact.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Conflict 3: Output filename**
> The template filename pattern is: `ResumeT - {Company name} - {Position name} - Wang Cuixia - {Generate date}.docx`
> After generation, the output should be: `Resume - AUT auto - Sales Consultant - WangCuixia - 20260226.docx`
>
> ✅ We will: replace [ResumeT](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/models/template.py#4-15) with [Resume](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/models/template.py#4-15) and `Cover LetterT` with `Cover Letter` in the filename, replace `{Company name}`, `{Position name}`, `{Generate date}` (and Chinese equivalents `{公司名称}`, `{职位名称}`) with actual values. The final filename is computed on the backend and included in the response.

> [!TIP]
> **Suggestion for the user:** The `{key: "explain"}` syntax is very flexible. For example, the user can write `{Content of Cover letter: 4 paragraphs, 1 page}` and that entire string after `:` becomes the generation instruction for that placeholder. This is backwards-compatible with simple `{key}` tokens.

---

## Proposed Changes

### Backend

---

#### [MODIFY] [template.py (model)](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/models/template.py)
- Add a `template_type` field: `str = "docx"` (or `"md"` for backwards compatibility with old templates)

#### [MODIFY] [template.py (schema)](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/schemas/template.py)
- Add `template_type: Optional[str] = "docx"` to [TemplateCreate](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/schemas/template.py#4-9) and [TemplateResponse](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/schemas/template.py#10-19)

#### [MODIFY] [templates.py (API)](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/api/v1/templates.py)
- Accept `template_content` as a Base64 string (no change needed to this file — the existing `POST /templates` simply stores whatever `template_content` string is sent)

#### [NEW] [docx_service.py](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/docx_service.py)
New helper service dedicated to [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) manipulation:
```python
# Key functions:
def extract_placeholders(docx_bytes: bytes) -> dict[str, str]:
    """
    Parse the .docx file and find all {key} or {key: explain} tokens.
    Returns: {"skills": "", "projects": "list 3 key projects", ...}
    Uses python-docx to iterate paragraphs and table cells.
    """

def replace_placeholders(docx_bytes: bytes, replacements: dict[str, str]) -> bytes:
    """
    For each {key} or {key: explain} token in paragraphs and table cells,
    replace entire token with replacements[key].
    Preserves run-level formatting by doing in-place text replacement.
    Returns: new docx as bytes
    """

def build_output_filename(template_filename: str, company: str, position: str, date_str: str) -> str:
    """
    Converts "ResumeT - {Company name} - {Position name} - Wang Cuixia - {Generate date}.docx"
    into   "Resume - AUT auto - Sales Consultant - WangCuixia - 20260226.docx"
    Also handles Chinese: {公司名称}, {职位名称}
    """
```

#### [MODIFY] [writer_service.py](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py)
- Add a new function `generate_content_for_keys(keys: dict, job, matched_blocks, language) -> dict[str, str]`
- This function builds the same context as before (job info + candidate experience), then asks the LLM to return a JSON object where each key maps to a generated text section
- The existing [generate_resume](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py#38-96) and [generate_cover_letter](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/services/writer_service.py#97-124) functions are **kept unchanged** for backwards compatibility but are no longer called when a [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) template is used

#### [MODIFY] [jobs.py (API)](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/api/v1/jobs.py)
- In [generate_job_resume](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/backend/app/api/v1/jobs.py#218-301) endpoint:
  - If template exists AND `template_type == "docx"`: use docx pipeline (extract → generate → replace → return binary)
  - Otherwise: fall back to existing markdown generation (backwards compatibility)
  - Change the response: instead of storing markdown in `generated_resume`, store the **Base64-encoded output docx** — OR — return a file directly via `FileResponse`
  
> [!WARNING]
> **Key Decision Required:** Currently `job.generated_resume` is a markdown text field stored in the DB. If we store a Base64 docx there, the download logic changes significantly on the frontend.
>
> **Recommended approach:** Add a **new API endpoint** `GET /jobs/{job_id}/download-resume` that generates and streams the [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) file directly (no change to DB schema needed). The existing `generated_resume` text field can remain for preview/display purposes.
>
> Actually, simpler: We can still store Base64 in `generated_resume`. The frontend download logic simply detects if the content is Base64 (starts with `PK` docx magic bytes decoded) and downloads it directly, bypassing the markdown→docx conversion. This avoids a new endpoint.

**Final decision (simplest path):**
- Store the generated [.docx](file:///c:/scripts/build/search_agent/testdata/ResumeT%20-%20%7BCompany%20name%7D%20-%20%7BPosition%20name%7D%20-%20Wang%20Cuixia%20-%20%7BGenerate%20date%7D.docx) as a **Base64 string** in `job.generated_resume`
- Keep `generated_resume` as a string column (no migration)  
- On the frontend, detect if content is Base64 docx or markdown, and handle accordingly

